Introduction¶

Somewhere in Brazil, in greater Vitória (east coast),

Maria and Ana are wating for Pedro. They are no friends, Pedro is 24 year old man having now a medical appointment in a hospital. Maria the doctor and her assitant Ana, are wating now already appr. 20 minutes. It seems Pedro can't make it today and forgot to cancel the appointment in advance. So Maria and Ana waisted a lot of time watining for Pedro.

Dataset Overview¶

The situation above keeps some fundamenatl problems, Maria and Ana have being waisting time, so economic consequences and of course the lost opportunity to take care on somebody else are related to Pedros behaviour. Furthermore Pedro might neglect his health. As a consequence one is interested what is the primary situation and reasons for not showing up. The investigated here, collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

Original Data Dictionary:

* = will be reformatted later ** = typos are from the original desctiption will be corrected later

Question to be adressed¶

The following questions will be adressed in this anaylisis to unleash patterns in the behaviour of patients, being able to use those as features for machine learning algorithms.

  1. Are women showing up more often then men?
  2. Do older people take there medical appointments more seriously?
  3. Do poor people tend to show up more often?
  4. Do SMS reminders decrese the no-show rate?
  5. Is there a particular day in the week which has a higher no-show rate?
  6. Is the time gap between making the appointmnet and the appointment itself in relation to the no-show rate

# standard figure size
fig_size=(10,10)

# function to easily calculate the proportion based on show/no-show and 
# input: dataframe , colum for add. groupby
# output: show no-show
def prop(df, column):
    # get counts for each show/no-show and add. attribute
    ns_counts = df.groupby(['No_Show', column]).count()['Appointment_ID']
    # get total appointmet counts for column
    column_totals = df.groupby(column).count()['Appointment_ID']
    # calculate Proportions for no-show
    no_show = ns_counts[1] / column_totals
    # calculate Proportions for show
    show = ns_counts[0] / column_totals
    return show, no_show

# function to easily calculate the proportion based on rows iterated e.g with apply
# input: value as nominator, totals, key 1, key 2
# output: proportion
def prop_rows(value, df_total, df_total_key1, df_total_key2):
    proportion = 0
    # check if value is greater 0 if not return 0
    if value > 0:
        # check if key or 2 keys passed to get the total value 
        if np.isnan(df_total_key2):
            total = df_total[df_total_key1]
        else:
            total = df_total[df_total_key1, df_total_key2]
            if total == 0:
                total = 1
    # finally calculate the proportion
    proportion = value / total
    return proportion

# function to plot bar chart
# https://matplotlib.org/examples/api/barchart_demo.html
# import: 
#      bar1: first bar (attribute1 by show / no-show)
#      bar1: 2nd bar   (attribute2 by show / no-show)
#      legend1 and legende2: txt elements for the legend
#      ylabel: txt for teh y axis
#      xlabel: txt ['txt1','txt2']
#      title: txt for title 
#      xlbl_pos: decimal for the x-label pos (in the bar) default = 1.05
#      xlbl_round: how to round teh decimals (in the bar) default = 2
# out:
#      no explicit returm the func will plot the bar chart

def two_bar_plots(bar1, bar2, legend1, legend2, ylabel, xlabel, title, xlbl_pos=1.05, xlbl_round = 2):

    
    # the x locations for the groups
    ind = np.arange(len(bar1))  
    # the width of the bars
    width = 0.35       

    # create the subplot with geenric figire size
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_size)

    # create the first bar 
    rects1 = ax.bar(ind, bar1, width, color='r', alpha=.7, label=legend1, bottom=bar2)

    #create teh 2nd bar
    rects2 = ax.bar(ind, bar2, width, color='g', alpha=.7, label=legend2,)

    # add some text for labels, title and axes ticks
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=20)
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=20)
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=20)
    ax.set_xticks(ind)
    labels = xlabel  # xtick labels
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels,fontsize=20)
    ax.legend(fontsize=20)


#   inside doing the labeling (see link on top)
    def autolabel(rects):
        """
        Attach a text label above each bar displaying its height
        """
        for rect in rects:
            height = rect.get_height()
            ax.text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width()/2., (1-height) * xlbl_pos,
                      round(height , xlbl_round),
                      ha='center', va='center', fontsize=20)
   
    # call the labeling         
    autolabel(rects2)
    autolabel(rects1)

Conclusions¶

  1. Are women showing up more often then men? 65,4% of all appointments are created by female patients. 34,6% are done by male patients.
    The no-show and show-up rate is nearly identical.
  • Male
    • Show: 79,8%
    • No-Show: 20,2%
  • Female
    • Show: 80,2%
    • No-Show: 19,8%

As a conclusion I state that there is no relationship between the no-show rate and gender.

  1. Do older people take there medical appointments more seriously?

The age ranges from 0 (new born childs) to 100 (after cleansing). Thre highets number of appointments is doen for the group 0 - 4 years. The proportion of no-show rate is increasing and finds a peak at 14 years. Another decrease in decrease in no-show rate is happening at the age of 63 to age 88. Simutaniously the number of appointmnets is decreasing starting as well here. The conclusion here is that there is a slight relationship between age and no-show rate. The higher teh age teh less data. It needs to be tested futher with moer data.

  1. Do poor people tend to show up more often?

9,8% received funds so let's compare that group with the group received no funds.

  • Scholarship
    • Show: 80,3%
    • No-Show: 19,7%
  • No-Scholarsip
    • Show: 76,4%
    • No-Show: 23,6%

There is a small difference in the outcome, which means the scholarship receiver no-show rate is 3,9% higher then the one of patients receiving no scholarship. So the conclusion here is that it is true, poor people have a lower no-show rate.

  1. Do SMS reminders decrese the no-show rate?

33,5% (so appr. 1/3) of all patients received one or more SMS messages before the appointment. Surprisingly the no-show rate of the ones received SMS messages is 11% higher than the ones which didn't receive a message at all.

  • No SMS Received
    • Show: 83,6%
    • No-Show: 16,4%
  • SMS Received
    • Show: 72,6%
    • No-Show: 27,4%

So the conclusion is that receiving an SMS isn't decreasing the no-show rate.

  1. Is there a particular day in the week which has a higher no-show rate?

There is no activity on Sunday, very little on Saturday.
From Friday to Saturday the no-show rate seems to be slightly higher then on the other days. On saturday the highest proportion is seen although the overall number of appointment is going to few.

  • Monday 20,70%
  • Tuesday 19,80%
  • Wednesday 19,50%
  • Thursday 19,20%
  • Friday 21,10%
  • Saturday 23,70%

So the conclusion is that each day is very close to each other, excpet Saturday but due to little data overservations here it will be concluded that ther eis no relationship between weekday and no-show rate.

  1. Is the time gap between making the appointmnet and the appointment itself in relation to the no-show rate

The time gaps ranges from 0 to 179 days! The highest count of time gap is actually 34275 for 0 time gap. The lowest no-show rate occurs if the day making the appointment is equal to the apppointmet day itself (4,1%). After that it ranges between 20% - 40%. If the time gap is above 100 days it is significantl higher. Although here the limitation is the number of observations. A meaningful amount of oberservations is given till a time gap of appr. 35 days. Taking this range into account there is a increase which sets teh conclusion that teh higher the gap between making teh appointment and the actual appointment date teh higher is the no-show rate.
